of ancient manners; domestic dramas featuring colorful heroes and heroines; pieces that introduce faddish Western properties and behavior; and a play that bridges the gap between the conventions of classical kabuki, Shakespeare, and modern psychological drama. Dominating the era are the works of Kawatake Mokuami, the last great kabuki playwright, while the dramaturgy of literary scholar Tsubouchi Shôyô brings kabuki into the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aBenkei, Funa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandon, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandon, James R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChöbei, Kiwametsuki Banzui, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJishi, Ren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJishi, Shunkyö Kagami, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeiter, Samuel L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeiter, Samuel L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOtoshi, Suö, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRakugetsu, Hototogisu Kojö, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShigeru, Onna Shosei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShinza, Kamiyui, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSögorö, Sakanaya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaiko, Sakai no, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uht